With the volume of NBA collaborations circulating lately, it made me stop and reflect on the value of collaboration. Coming up, the NBA license was sacred and the league guarded its property to a very strict standard. It’s why my work had to uphold artistic integrity— because earning this license was (and remains) a privilege. 

Throughout all of my NBA licensed projects, the  goal has been to elevate not just the brand I’m working for (whether my own, or on a corporate level) but also the NBA’s. 

Here’s a look at some of the NBA projects I’ve worked on in recent years.

While I enjoy seeing what’s out there today, I really haven’t seen anyone else take my approach  to NBA tees.  During my time at Nike, I made an effort to authenticate designs by bringing in Shirt Kings, Pen & Pixel and Filip Pagowski for original pieces.  I felt it was a way to give artists that shaped the culture their due. I had to push really hard internally and put up many fights to get these through. But I haven’t seen anything better since. 

Can’t wait to Launch NBA x Trophy Hunting® next…. Y’all have been warned. 😎
.
.
.

@Converse x @t__cloud9 By DOC® 🌩️
This was the first tee I worked on out of the 4 and it’s definitely my favorite. It has the nostalgia of the early 90s caricatures but feels even more relevant now. Shout out to T Cloud for always repping. Philly always in the building🏆
.
.
.

I’m really proud of this series. I grew up recreating the caricature tees of the 90’s and since then I’ve illustrated caricature tees for every brand I’ve worked for (Even before the 90’s were deemed ‘nostalgic’-Check my receipts). I’ve always wanted to put my spin on them, so when Converse called I was really excited to partner with both the brand and their roster of athletes. I’ve always felt that my ability to tell authentic stories through design was what separated me from other “caricature artists.” If you look into the details you can see that there’s more to the tee than just the player. Thanks @_stelly_ & the crew from @Converse for the opportunity to share my art. 

Check out my website/news to see the latest edition to my Converse Artist Series. More sketches coming soon. 
.

My career started at AND 1 in 1999. I call it my masters degree in the basketball & footwear industry. As a young designer I was able to learn all aspects of the design process on the job thanks to some amazing founders/mentors and colleagues that gave me the opportunity to learn on the fly. My on the job training resulted in pivotal work in And 1’s history. Even 30 years later I smile when I see the work I did from 2 decades ago, randomly appear anywhere from a movie to the streets. 

This year marks the 30th anniversary of AND 1. As part of the original founded company, I am so proud to have been able to work and witness such a legendary time. 

Here’s a walk down memory lane of some of my favorite designs, down to my desk & workspace (with a view of the basketball court😎) at the time. 
.
.

Logo Concept Proposal for Sabrina Ionescu.
Before she was drafted I was asked to pitch an identity for Sabrina. Here’s a little snippet of the presentation. 
There is a lot of research, trial and error and strategy that  goes into creating an identity. It’s not just finding a clever way of mixing a number and letters or some sort of monogram. Good logos to me are the ones that have deeper meaning that reveal itself over time. Good logos can tell a story and be extremely simple at the same time they  look like it took you 5 minutes to create. You never see the hundreds of versions, pages of notes, conversations and revisions that go into the final output. I love working with athletes to create their identities because it challenges me to portray the essence of an athlete and person, by creating a symbol out of a few lines and shapes. Even though this logo was not chosen, I learned a lot about Sabrina in creating it, I’m glad she’s gotten her own signature shoe (and logo) with Nike. She is the future. 👁️🏆🏀
.

Happy 50th bday hip hop.
Throughout my career I’ve used hip hop and basketball as inspiration in my work. 

I’ve blinged out tees in Pen & Pixel Style for AND 1, placed countless lyrics on tees, reimagined the 80’s Caricature tees for Biggie and Tupac (via UNDRCRWN®), designed a basketball jersey and short inspired by Biggie, and eventually collaborated with Shirtkings and  Pen & Pixel for Nike Basketball.

Throughout this process I’ve been able to work with some of the most legendary figures in hip hop. I’m still inspired and I continue to grow. I’m proud that I’ve been able to add to the history and  culture through art and design. 

Most recently I’ve been working on a collection of illustrations  that combine my experiences in Sports+Hip Hop+ Art, so stay tuned for more on that.

 #ballharder #hiphop50

This 13 piece collection in collaboration with the massive brand @puma. (3 footwear styles. 10 apparel pieces (4 of which are unisex))is the final result of 2 years of my life.
Day trips to Puma’s US Headquarters in Boston for fittings, design reviews.
Breaking bread, sharing war stories with Cruz @kidcarlyle @goodhight & the puma team. 
Inspirational convos with @vegas_jones @juneambrose. 
Hours of  debate with @cruziiie while meticulously editing the final product, making sure we weren’t making something that we didn’t believe in. FaceTiming @jgtradition while he was driving and looking at the samples when they came in. 
4 photoshoots with our amazing friends/peers, 
Creating a launch strategy and making sure that everything we we wanted got executed no matter how tired we were. 
With all that said, a lot of time and people made this collection what it is. But the time we spent with these people was why this is a special moment. Thank you to everyone that participated in “Celebrating the Journey” with us. I hope when you put the product on you feel what we feel making it.

Celebrate the process.🥂
.

"The Bay Makes The World Takes” By DOC® for Oaklandish available at 10am PST / 1pm EST @ Link in bio. 

This 7-piece capsule pays homage to my roots as a designer, artist,  and Bay Area native celebrating The Bay’s global influence.

The Bay has historically thrived by embracing its uniqueness and fostering local talent. Our validation often originates within our communities first, not through external opinion.

But when @tooshort moved to Atlanta and the Raiders left The Town for L.A., the notion of having to leave the Bay for ‘better opportunities’ was first planted in my mind. Up until that point, I was surrounded by the culture and passion of landmark moments like the A’s winning the World Series, the 49ers dominating football, and Run TMC performing in front of the livest NBA audiences.

So when I too, chose to ‘leave the Bay’ and pursue my dream of becoming a designer, it put back into focus what I had actually left behind. I saw the uniqueness of my influences and upbringing as an asset. My surroundings instilled a particular kind of grit, hustle, and underdog mentality in me. I’ve carried this mentality and inspiration everywhere I go. 

This capsule celebrates those who spread Bay Area culture wherever they arrive. Unlike teams that leave the Bay— when locals leave ‘The Town’, they forever carry its essence within them.

#thebaymakestheworldtakes
